telldus-core C++ code (built in our Dockerfile) — this is the telldusd daemon. It contains all the protocol encoders (arctech, everflourish, etc.) that generate raw pulse strings internally. When you call tdTurnOn(device_id), the C++ code builds the pulse string (like S$k$k...+ or T\x7f\xff...+) and sends it directly to the FTDI USB chip. The raw bytes never leave the C++ process — no encoding issues.

TellStick firmware (runs on the ATmega chip inside the USB stick) — receives the raw pulse bytes from the FTDI and drives the 433 MHz transmitter. We don't touch this.

Our Python integration (client.py) — talks to telldusd over TCP/socat. When we try tdSendRawCommand, the raw bytes go: Python → TCP → socat → UNIX socket → telldusd's Socket::read() → charToWstring() (UTF-8 conversion) → mangled.

The bug is in telldusd's IPC layer (the Socket::read() function in telldus-core), which treats all incoming data as UTF-8 text. Our Luxorparts byte 225 (0xE1) gets interpreted as the start of a 3-byte UTF-8 sequence, followed by non-continuation bytes, causing corruption → error -5.

Since we already patch telldus-core in the Dockerfile, we can absolutely add another patch to fix this. The simplest approach would be to patch Socket::read() in common/Socket_unix.cpp to do byte-by-byte conversion (Latin-1) instead of UTF-8, which would make tdSendRawCommand binary-safe.

