Here's a summary of what was done:

Fix: Binary-safe tdSendRawCommand via telldus-core Dockerfile patch
Root cause: telldusd's IPC layer converts all socket data through iconv(UTF-8 → WCHAR_T). Byte 225 (0xE1) — our Luxorparts inter-packet gap — is a UTF-8 3-byte lead byte. When the next bytes aren't continuation bytes, iconv fails, the data is truncated, and sendRawCommand returns -5 (TELLSTICK_ERROR_COMMUNICATION).

Why existing protocols work: All working Duo protocols (arctech, everflourish, etc.) generate their raw pulse strings inside the C++ code — the bytes never cross the IPC boundary. tdSendRawCommand is the only path where raw pulse bytes traverse the socket, and it was broken for any value ≥ 0x80.

Fix (cloned functions, originals untouched):

File	Change
Strings.h	Declare charToWstringRaw() + wideToStringRaw()
Strings.cpp	Implement both — byte-by-byte Latin-1, no iconv
Socket_unix.cpp	Socket::read() → uses charToWstringRaw()
DeviceManager.cpp	sendRawCommand() → uses wideToStringRaw()
The original charToWstring()/wideToString() are not modified — all existing protocols (arctech, everflourish, hasta, etc.) continue using the original UTF-8 path unchanged.

