Troubleshooting duo and znet reaction issues
27m 27s
Now to answer your questions directly:

Root Cause Found: Firmware Buffer Overflow 🎯
Why neither the Duo nor ZNet flash or react:

TellStick Duo
The Duo firmware (usart.c) has a 512-byte receive buffer. Our Luxorparts command was embedding 10 repeats of 52-byte packets directly in the S data:

Code
S<520 bytes of pulse data>+  →  521 bytes in buffer  →  OVERFLOW!
When bufferP >= 512, the firmware wraps to 0, overwrites the S command byte at position 0 with a pulse data byte, and handleMessage() hits the default case → prints "Unknown command" → no transmission, no LED flash.

Fix applied: Changed to use the firmware's built-in R<count> repeat prefix:

Code
R<10>S<52 bytes single packet>+  →  56 bytes  →  fits perfectly!
The firmware already supports this (see case 'R': in handleMessage()). It repeats the single packet internally with 11ms pause between each.

TellStick ZNet
The ZNet path falls through to turn_on(device_id) because TellStickNetController doesn't have send_raw_command. Since luxorparts isn't a native telldusd protocol, this silently fails. The ZNet firmware also has known bugs with raw S bytes (crashes on missing protocol key). ZNet Luxorparts support needs a separate approach.

Regarding USB bypass (your questions)
Can we bypass telldus-core for the Duo? Yes, technically — we could talk to the FTDI chip directly via pyftdi or libftdi. The firmware accepts commands over the USART (9600 baud): R<count>P<pause>S<pulse_data>+. But there's no real benefit — the firmware buffer overflow was the actual issue, not telldus-core. With the R-prefix fix, the standard tdSendRawCommand → controller->send() path should work correctly.

Would direct USB give better control? Not significantly. The firmware is the bottleneck — it's a fixed PIC18 microcontroller. All commands go through the same USART regardless of how they arrive at the FTDI chip.

