3 Critical Bugs Found
Bug #1 — WRONG BIT PATTERN (bit extraction offset)

The ground truth hex codes (e.g. 0x5E14538) are 28-bit values. The real 25-bit code occupies the top 25 bits; the bottom 3 bits are zero padding. My encoder reads bits 24..0 (bottom 25) instead of bits 27..3 (top 25):

Code
Full 28-bit:  0101 1110 0001 0100 0101 0011 1|000
              └──── correct 25 bits ──────┘ └pad┘

Encoder reads:  |111 1000 0101 0001 0100 1110 00
                  └──── WRONG 25 bits ──────────┘
Correct: 12 ones + 13 zeros → 12 short gaps + 13 long gaps
My encoder: 11 ones + 14 zeros → 11 short gaps + 14 long gaps ← matches rtl_433!
This confirms the encoder is transmitting the wrong data bits.

Bug #2 — WRONG MODULATION SCHEME (PWM vs PPM)

My encoder produces OOK-PWM (bit value encoded in pulse width):

Bit 0: 380µs pulse + 1120µs gap
Bit 1: 1120µs pulse + 380µs gap
Telldus Live uses OOK-PPM (bit value encoded in gap width, pulse always fixed):

Bit 0: 392µs pulse + 1112µs gap
Bit 1: 392µs pulse + 352µs gap
Strangely, rtl_433 sees all pulses at ~400µs from my implementation (not the expected mix of 380µs and 1120µs). The firmware may be re-interpreting the S-command bytes as timing indices rather than raw durations, or there's something else happening. Either way, the encoding needs to be changed to PPM: same pulse byte for all bits, only the gap byte varies.

Bug #3 — INTER-PACKET GAP TOO LONG (4.4×)

Telldus Live: ~2252µs between packets
My implementation: ~10004µs (firmware R-repeat uses hardcoded ~11ms pause)
Ratio: 4.4× too long
The firmware's R<count> repeat command has a fixed ~11ms inter-repeat delay that can't be changed. To get the correct ~2.25ms gap, the repeats must be embedded in the S data itself (not using firmware R-repeat).

Fix Required
Right-shift codes by 3 before encoding (or use n_bits=28) to extract the correct 25 bits
Change encoder to PPM: pulse byte is always t_pulse (~39), gap byte alternates between t_gap_short (~35) and t_gap_long (~111)
Embed repeats in S data instead of using firmware R-prefix, so inter-packet gap is controlled by our gap_inter byte (~2250µs)
