What are those "Action required" CI runs?

Those are your CI workflow (ci.yaml) — the linting pipeline (Hadolint, Shellcheck, YAMLlint, JSON lint, App lint). Every time I (Copilot) push a commit to the branch, GitHub automatically triggers a CI run.

Why do they say "Action required" instead of showing ✅ or ❌?

This is a GitHub security feature called "first-party fork approval". When a workflow is triggered by a push from a bot account (like Copilot), GitHub pauses the workflow and marks it "Action required" — meaning you (the repo owner) need to manually click "Approve and run" before the CI jobs will execute. This is to prevent bots from running potentially dangerous CI workflows without human oversight.

The CI runs triggered by your own pushes show ✅ or ❌ normally. Only the ones triggered by the Copilot bot get held for approval.

Do you need to run them before creating releases?

No. These are just linting checks (shellcheck, hadolint, yamllint, etc.). They don't build anything or create releases. Your release workflows (Create Test Release, Create Stable Release, Deploy) are separate and triggered manually or by tags. You can safely ignore the "Action required" CI runs — they're just queued lint checks waiting for your approval.

